               </p>
            </p>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>Replacing the mixing arm scrapers:</p>
            <p>
               <ul>
                  <li>The scraper (2) is a sealing ring that is inserted into the same drilled hole in the rotor into which the mixing arm is inserted.  (See image in step 3 above.)</li>
                  <li>The scrapers can only be replaced after the mixing arms have been removed.</li>
               </ul>
            </p>
         </li>
         <li>
            <p>Replacing the mixing paddles:</p>
            <p>
               <ul>
                  <li>Undo the screws (1), and remove the paddles (2).</li>
                  <li>Before installing the new mixing paddles, soak an intermediate textile or
                     paper gasket layer (3) in water.</li>
                  <li>Place the paper layer between the mounting part and the mixing paddle.</li>
                  <li>Ensure that the mixing paddles (2) are attached so that their top edge
                     overlaps the mounting part.</li>
                  <li>Readjust the paddle height using the slotted holes.</li>
                  <li>Before tightening up the fastening screws, make sure that there is a parallel
                     gap between the bottom of the paddle and the trough floor wear liner (1-2 mm,
                     or 0.04 to 0.08 inch).</li>
               </ul>
               <note type="note" id="note_z5w_s1s_lcc">
                  <p>Re-tighten theconnection between the mixing paddles and the scraper paddles
                     after five hours of operating time.</p>
               </note>
               <note type="note" id="note_avw_s1s_lcc">
                  <p>Inspect all mixing paddles at regular interval s for wear and damage. Replace
                     if necessary. Using worn or damaged paddles can lead to serious damage to the
                     mixer.</p>
               </note>
